Amil Umraw, The Witness (File) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Pietermaritzburg - An Underberg farmer was taken to hospital in a serious condition after an unknown number of men attacked him on his farm on Wednesday. KwaZulu-Natal police spokesperson Lieutenant Nqobile Gwala said the 47-year-old farmer was approached by the men who assaulted him before stealing his Toyota Hilux bakkie at about 4.30 am yesterday.Gwala said some of the farmer&rsquo;s &ldquo;personal belongings&rdquo;, including his licensed firearm, were also stolen when the suspects took the bakkie.&ldquo;He [the farmer] was taken to hospital in a serious condition. A case of car hijacking was opened at Himeville police station for investigation and no arrest has been made at this stage,&rdquo; Gwala said.&ldquo;The farmer&rsquo;s bakkie was later recovered in the Kilmun area.&rdquo;The attack comes amid threatening messages sent to farmers in Mpumalanga.Yesterday, News24 reported that Mpumalanga police were investigating a threatening SMS that was sent to five farmers in Ermelo, giving them an ultimatum to vacate their land or be forcefully removed.Ermelo police spokesperson Captain Carla Prinsloo told a News24 correspondent that two cases of intimidation had been opened over the alarming messages.The SMS reads: &ldquo;Vacate your land whyte [sic] man or we will forse [sic] you. Take your wife and children away. We will visit them.&rdquo;&ldquo;There are no relationships between the farmers, except that they all live in this district and that all the SMSes came from the same number. There was no mention of a deadline for the farmers to vacate their farms,&rdquo; Prinsloo said.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.